Some analyses on PhD graduates in Canada

Ming Ming Zhang

2019-04-15

Abstract

We are interested in some statistics on PhD graduates in Canada, specially in population of PhD graduates and who pursued further education after PhD graduation. The data is extracted from National graduates survey, postsecondary graduates by province of study and level of study, Table 37-10-0030-01, Statistics Canada.

Our analyses show that the population of PhD graduates in Canada had a decrease from 2000 to 2005, and an increase from 2005 to 2010. In particular, British Columbia had the most decrease from 2000 to 2005; Quebec had the most growth from 2005 to 2010; and from 2000 to 2010, Saskatchewan had the most growth.

Interestingly, in the population of PhD graduates in Canada, there are some graduates who pursued further education after graduation. We found that the PhD graduates in Alberta who pursued further education after graduation is the only province in Canada had a decrease from 2000 to 2010; in the contrast, British Columbia and Ontario shared the most growth. The results are interpreted as geographic patterns in the map of Canada.

We use the following abbreviations for provinces and territories.

G$GEO1 = factor(G$GEO, levels = c("Canada","Alberta","British Columbia","Manitoba","New Brunswick","Newfoundland and Labrador","Nova Scotia","Ontario","Prince Edward Island","Quebec","Saskatchewan"), labels = c("CA","AB","BC","MB","NB","NL","NS","ON","PE","QC","SK"))

Let \(Population\; I\) denote the number of PhD graduates in certain year.

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(G[G$UOM=="Number",],aes(x=GEO1,y=VALUE)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1),axis.title.x=element_blank(),axis.title.y=element_blank()) +
  facet_grid(~REF_DATE) +
  labs(title = "Population I by Province in 2000, 2005 and 2010")
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

The above figure shows that Canada had a decrease in \(Population\; I\) from 2000 to 2005, and Canada had an increase in \(Population\; I\) from 2005 to 2010.

Let \(Population\; II\) denote the number of PhD graduates pursued further education after graduation in certain year. When we say \(percentage\; Population\; II\), we mean percentage of \(Population\; II\) in \(Population\; I\).

ggplot(G[G$UOM=="Percentage",],aes(x=GEO1,y=VALUE)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1),axis.title.x=element_blank(),axis.title.y=element_blank()) +
  facet_grid(~REF_DATE) +
  labs(title = "Percentage Population II by Province in 2000, 2005 and 2010")

It follows that Canada had a decrease in \(Population\; II\) from 2000 to 2005, and Canada had an increase in \(Population\; II\) from 2005 to 2010.

Next we will investigate the changes in \(Population\; I\) and \(II\) by province.

G2000 = G[G$REF_DATE==2000,]

G2000 = G2000[,-1]

names(G2000)[3] = "V2000"

G2005 = G[G$REF_DATE==2005,]

G2005 = G2005[,-1]

names(G2005)[3] = "V2005"

G2010 = G[G$REF_DATE==2010,]

G2010 = G2010[,-1]

names(G2010)[3] = "V2010"
G1 = merge(merge(G2000,G2005),G2010)

G1 = G1[order(G1$GEO),]

We calculate the percentage of changes in \(Population\; I\) and \(II\) as follows.

G1$`C2000-05` = ifelse(G1$V2000==0,NA,(G1$V2005 - G1$V2000)/G1$V2000)
G1$`C2005-10` = ifelse(G1$V2005==0,NA,(G1$V2010 - G1$V2005)/G1$V2005)
G1$`C2000-10` = ifelse(G1$V2000==0,NA,(G1$V2010 - G1$V2000)/G1$V2000)

In the period of 2000 to 2010, British Columbia and Ontario shared the most population II growth; in the contrast Alberta had a decrease.

It would be interesting to see if there are geographic patterns to the percentage of changes in \(Population\; I\) and \(II\) in the different provinces.

Recall the map of Canada by province, which can be found in 2016 Census - Boundary files, Statistics Canada.

library(rgdal)

canada.raw = readOGR(dsn = "~/Downloads/gpr_000b11a_e", layer = "gpr_000b11a_e", use_iconv=TRUE, encoding="CP1250")

library(geojsonio)

canada.raw.json = geojson_json(canada.raw)

library(rmapshaper)

canada.raw.sim = ms_simplify(canada.raw.json)

geojson_write(canada.raw.sim, file = "~/Documents/Maps/canada.geojson")
library(sf)
## Warning: package 'sf' was built under R version 3.5.2
## Linking to GEOS 3.6.1, GDAL 2.1.3, PROJ 4.9.3
canada.map = st_read(dsn = "~/Documents/Maps/canada.geojson", quiet = TRUE)

canada.map = st_transform(canada.map, crs = "+proj=lcc +lat_1=49 +lat_2=77 +lon_0=-91.52 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs")

names(canada.map)[3] = "Province"

ggplot(data = canada.map, mapping = aes(fill = Province)) +
  geom_sf(size = 0.01) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_blank(),axis.text.y=element_blank(),axis.ticks.x=element_blank(),axis.ticks.y=element_blank()) +
  labs(title = "The Map of Canada by Province")

We provide different groups of \(Population\; I\) and \(II\) in the year 2010 in maps.

GP1$Gps = cut(GP1$V2010,quantile(GP1$V2010,(0:3)/3),include.lowest = T)

GP1 = subset(GP1, GEO1!="CA")
P1 = canada.map

P1$Groups = GP1$Gps[match(canada.map$Province,GP1$GEO)]
P1[,c("Province","Groups")]
